### Automatically Generate a Table of Contents in LaTeX

To automatically generate a table of contents in LaTeX, you can use the following commands:

1. **\tableofcontents**: This command generates the table of contents itself.
2. **\addcontentsline**: This command adds an entry to the table of contents.

Here's an example of how to use these commands:

```  
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}
\tableofcontents
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction.
\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.
\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.
\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.
\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.
\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.
\section{Results}
This is the results section.
\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.
\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.
\section{Discussion}
This is the discussion section.
\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.
\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.
\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command generates the table of contents at the beginning of the document. The `\addcontentsline` command is used to add entries to the table of contents for each section and subsection. The syntax for `\addcontentsline` is as follows:

```  
\addcontentsline{<file>}{<level>}{<text>}
```

- `<file>`: The name of the file where the table of contents is stored. This is usually `toc`.
- `<level>`: The level of the entry in the table of contents. This can be `section`, `subsection`, `subsubsection`, etc.
- `<text>`: The text that will appear in the table of contents.

In the example above, the `\addcontentsline` command is used to add entries for each section and subsection. The `<level>` is set to `section` for the main sections and `subsection` for the subsections. The `<text>` is set to the section or subsection title.

By default, the table of contents is generated automatically when the document is compiled. However, you can also manually generate the table of contents by using the `\tableofcontents` command in the preamble of the document. This will generate the table of contents at the beginning of the document, but you will need to manually update it if you add or remove sections or subsections.

